WEBVTT

00:06.570 --> 00:10.070
MIDGE:
The one that got away.

00:10.110 --> 00:12.400
The biggest heartache
of my life was not

00:12.450 --> 00:15.070
my husband and the father
of my children leaving me,

00:15.120 --> 00:19.950
it was never being able to
truly land Manniford McClaine.

00:20.000 --> 00:21.200
(group chuckling)

00:21.250 --> 00:23.170
Yes, that was his real name,

00:23.210 --> 00:25.080
and he was fabulous.

00:25.130 --> 00:27.670
He was the captain of
my high school football team.

00:27.710 --> 00:29.800
He was the leader of the pack.

00:29.840 --> 00:31.970
He had a jawline you could
stab your sister with.

00:32.009 --> 00:34.180
-(laughter)
-He was so gorgeous that

00:34.220 --> 00:35.840
after years of having
my mother tell me,

00:35.890 --> 00:38.220
"Your virtue is a garden,
keep it watered,

00:38.260 --> 00:39.930
but behind a fence,"

00:39.970 --> 00:41.810
I bring him over for dinner,
she takes one look at him,

00:41.850 --> 00:43.060
and suddenly it's like,
"You know what?

00:43.100 --> 00:44.310
"It's not a high fence.

00:44.350 --> 00:45.900
-"Just hop on over.
-(laughter)

00:45.940 --> 00:48.230
Here, step on my hands,
I'll give you a boost."

00:48.270 --> 00:50.230
-(laughter) -We almost
went to prom together.

00:50.280 --> 00:53.820
-ALL: Ooh!
-As friends, but still.

00:53.860 --> 00:56.910
Then his old girlfriend, Satan,
moved back from Rhode Island

00:56.950 --> 00:58.910
and they got back together,
got married,

00:58.950 --> 01:01.160
had four kids
and bought a waterfront mansion

01:01.200 --> 01:02.410
-in Oyster Bay.
-ALL: Ooh!

01:02.450 --> 01:03.660
Yes. And...

01:03.710 --> 01:05.040
Hey, is there any more
onion dip?

01:05.080 --> 01:06.170
ALL:
Shh!

01:06.210 --> 01:07.580
Sorry.

01:07.630 --> 01:08.960
(whispers):
Is there any more onion dip?

01:09.000 --> 01:10.920
-(laughter)
-Continue, please.

01:10.960 --> 01:13.880
Anyhow, the other day
I picked up a newspaper

01:13.920 --> 01:15.970
and there on the front page
is a headline:

01:16.010 --> 01:19.890
"Wall Street golden boy,
Manniford McClaine,

01:19.930 --> 01:24.350
caught with head of wife
in trunk of car."

01:24.390 --> 01:25.310
(all gasping)

01:25.350 --> 01:27.020
That's right.

01:27.060 --> 01:28.520
Manniford murdered his wife,

01:28.560 --> 01:30.020
then drove around
with her head for an hour

01:30.070 --> 01:31.610
before getting caught.
I couldn't believe it.

01:31.650 --> 01:34.110
It-it had to be some other
Manniford McClaine.

01:34.150 --> 01:36.450
But there he was,
in the paper, handcuffed,

01:36.490 --> 01:37.990
being perp-walked
into the station.

01:38.030 --> 01:40.740
And I just thought, "My God...

01:40.780 --> 01:43.160
he still looks fantastic."

01:43.200 --> 01:45.250
-(laughter)
-No, I mean it,

01:45.290 --> 01:47.870
better looking than high school.
I know,

01:47.920 --> 01:50.090
my first thought should've been,
"Dodged that bullet."

01:50.130 --> 01:54.630
Instead it was, "I don't know,
he's single, I'm single.

01:54.670 --> 01:56.800
If he beats this thing..."

01:56.840 --> 01:59.510
-(laughter) -Okay,
I'm gonna stop talking now.

01:59.550 --> 02:01.510
Harriet's brother is supposed
to play something for us.

02:01.560 --> 02:03.220
Tommy? Play me off!

02:03.270 --> 02:04.930
(cheering and applause)

02:04.980 --> 02:06.230
(piano playing)

02:06.270 --> 02:08.270
Thank you.
(laughs)

02:08.310 --> 02:10.020
Oh. Thanks.

02:11.570 --> 02:12.820
Onion dip.

02:15.780 --> 02:19.450
♫

02:19.490 --> 02:22.160
-♪ Bye bye love ♪
-Yes!

02:22.200 --> 02:25.410
♪ Bye bye happiness... ♪

02:25.450 --> 02:27.210
Vivian, you're out of glasses.

02:27.250 --> 02:30.000
Thanks for pointing out the
painfully obvious, Frederick.

02:30.040 --> 02:31.880
Stay vigilant!

02:32.920 --> 02:34.550
I think I'm in love
with Frederick.

02:34.590 --> 02:36.550
Frederick?
He's with Letty in toiletries.

02:36.590 --> 02:38.220
Letty dumped him days ago.

02:38.260 --> 02:40.340
I heard he was in love
with Carroll in the back office.

02:40.390 --> 02:41.600
-Who's she?
-He.

02:41.640 --> 02:42.970
How very Grecian.

02:43.010 --> 02:44.430
That is a terrible rumor
to spread.

02:44.470 --> 02:45.890
These are getting heavy.

02:45.930 --> 02:47.560
Counter.

02:47.600 --> 02:49.390
Use plastic cups next time.

02:49.440 --> 02:51.480
Pay for 'em and I'll use 'em.

02:51.520 --> 02:53.980
Give me that.
Were you raised by bears?

02:56.570 --> 02:57.780
Thanks, Mary.

02:57.820 --> 02:59.110
Coming through!

03:01.870 --> 03:03.490
-♪ Hello emptiness ♪
-Careful.

03:03.530 --> 03:05.330
Watch it.

03:05.370 --> 03:06.870
This is a balance issue, people.

03:06.910 --> 03:09.580
♪ Bye bye, my love,
good-bye-eye ♪

03:09.620 --> 03:11.790
♪ Bye bye,
my love, good-bye-eye. ♪

03:11.830 --> 03:15.000
Well done.

03:15.050 --> 03:17.050
(cheering and laughter)

03:20.550 --> 03:22.510
(in German accent): Oh, I'm so
Dasen-offen-upsetten-gruber.

03:22.550 --> 03:24.050
-(man shushes)
-I'm sorry?

03:24.100 --> 03:25.680
Fraulein, please help me.
I'm so lost.

03:25.720 --> 03:27.930
-I'm looking for the Reichstag.
-The Reichstag?

03:27.970 --> 03:29.770
You don't know this famous
German building?

03:29.810 --> 03:31.770
Gaudy, very big,
and no elevator?

03:31.810 --> 03:34.560
Oy, those steps will leave you
uber-pooped! Ha.

03:34.610 --> 03:36.940
-(laughter) -MIDGE: You look
very familiar to me.

03:36.980 --> 03:40.320
-Do I know you? -No, no, I just
have one of those punims.

03:40.360 --> 03:42.070
-(laughter)
-What's your name?

03:42.110 --> 03:43.620
My name, well, it's Ay-Rolf--

03:43.660 --> 03:45.160
that's the first name--

03:45.200 --> 03:46.410
"Jawohl," that's it.

03:46.450 --> 03:48.080
-Not very common.
-Ay-Rolf.

03:48.120 --> 03:49.330
Uh, and your last name?

03:49.370 --> 03:50.500
Hitler... burg.

03:50.540 --> 03:51.790
-(laughter)
-MIDGE: Well,

03:51.830 --> 03:53.750
I've got to tell you,
Mr. Ay-Rolf Hitlerburg,

03:53.790 --> 03:56.380
you're a pretty long way
from the Reichstag.

03:56.420 --> 03:59.090
Well, that bitch Himmler sent me
off completely unprepared.

03:59.130 --> 04:00.340
Did I say "Himmler"?

04:00.380 --> 04:01.880
I meant "Himmlerstein."

04:01.930 --> 04:03.260
Well, what were his directions?

04:03.300 --> 04:05.140
He said to take a left,
and another left,

04:05.180 --> 04:06.720
-and then the Third Reich.
-"Right."

04:06.760 --> 04:07.970
That's what I said:
"Third Reich."

04:08.010 --> 04:10.020
-"Right."
-Glad you agree.

04:10.060 --> 04:11.850
-(laughter)
-MIDGE: Well,

04:11.890 --> 04:13.520
you are a long way
from the fatherland.

04:13.560 --> 04:15.940
Was is das?

04:15.980 --> 04:17.940
Your German vocabulary's quite
impressive, by the way.

04:17.980 --> 04:20.860
-Danke.
-You are in New York City.

04:20.899 --> 04:23.030
New York City, interesting.

04:23.070 --> 04:25.320
Any place you can recommend
for a quick bite to eat?

04:25.370 --> 04:27.030
I'm feeling a bit peckish.

04:27.080 --> 04:29.080
Oh, well, there's an excellent
deli around the corner.

04:29.120 --> 04:32.000
-Yeah, deli's not really
my thing. -(laughter)

04:32.040 --> 04:33.330
Okay, what do you like?

04:33.370 --> 04:35.460
Whatever's fascist. Fastest!

04:35.500 --> 04:37.040
Oy, what a day this has been.

04:37.090 --> 04:38.590
(laughter)

04:38.630 --> 04:40.880
-(doorbell buzzes)
-Pizza's here! Everybody pay up!

04:40.920 --> 04:43.170
(applause, Midge laughs)

04:43.220 --> 04:44.680
So, I'm not really
Ay-Rolf Hitlerburg.

04:44.720 --> 04:46.180
Well, you had me fooled.

04:46.220 --> 04:48.100
I'm Randall,
Vivian's fifth favorite cousin.

04:48.140 --> 04:49.470
Midge,
Vivian's 34th best friend.

04:49.510 --> 04:50.720
VIVIAN:
My what?

04:50.770 --> 04:52.100
Nothing.

04:52.140 --> 04:54.270
-Couple of comedians.
-Are you?

04:54.310 --> 04:55.560
-Am I what?
-A comedian?

04:55.600 --> 04:57.110
Oh, bad sign if you can't tell.

04:57.150 --> 04:59.110
-No, you're hysterical.
-I'll take your pity.

04:59.150 --> 05:01.280
Yes, I've been at it a while.
Almost made my living from it.

05:01.320 --> 05:04.820
Got an agent, got a manager,
toured, did a little TV.

05:04.860 --> 05:06.820
(scoffs)
In fact, I got to go.

05:06.870 --> 05:09.950
-I got a set downtown
in a half hour. -Oh.

05:09.990 --> 05:11.620
Crappy time slot, but, oh, well.

05:11.660 --> 05:13.710
-You ever try a brisket?
-A brisket?

05:13.750 --> 05:15.080
Personal joke.

05:15.120 --> 05:16.210
See you again.

05:16.250 --> 05:17.420
And don't be funny without me.

05:17.460 --> 05:18.960
(chuckles)

05:19.000 --> 05:20.840
You can't have Randall,
I'm in love with him.

05:20.880 --> 05:22.380
He's your cousin, Vivian.

05:22.420 --> 05:23.920
Twice removed.

05:23.970 --> 05:25.220
Let's talk, sweetie.

05:25.260 --> 05:27.680
♪ ♪

05:33.560 --> 05:37.480
♪ I'm strictly a female female ♪

05:37.520 --> 05:41.270
♪ And my future I hope will be ♪

05:41.320 --> 05:44.030
♪ In the home of a brave ♪

05:44.070 --> 05:45.320
♪ And free male ♪

05:45.360 --> 05:48.360
♪ Who'll enjoy being a guy ♪

05:48.410 --> 05:51.280
♪ Having a girl... ♪

05:51.330 --> 05:53.370
Hey, Jack Webb. Do I look like
someone who would use anything

05:53.410 --> 05:54.830
you sell in this store?

05:54.870 --> 05:56.660
Follow the men shopping
for their mistresses.

05:56.710 --> 05:57.960
It's bound to be more fun.

05:58.000 --> 06:00.340
MIDGE:
This is a personal favorite.

06:00.380 --> 06:02.210
But this one's a little bit
more dramatic.

06:02.250 --> 06:04.300
You let me know if anything
speaks to you.

06:04.340 --> 06:06.010
WOMAN:
Oh, I don't know.

06:06.050 --> 06:08.220
I've never worn
much makeup before.

06:08.260 --> 06:09.510
This was my daughter's idea.

06:09.550 --> 06:11.640
Blue would be a wonderful color
on you.

06:11.680 --> 06:13.060
I don't know.

06:13.100 --> 06:15.230
-Which one is that again?
-Mermaid Ice.

06:15.270 --> 06:16.680
Would you like to try it on?

06:16.730 --> 06:17.890
-I don't know.
-Here.

06:17.940 --> 06:21.020
My daughter said
I should try more.

06:21.060 --> 06:23.020
She says I should live a little
before it's all over.

06:23.070 --> 06:24.280
Before what's all over?

06:24.320 --> 06:26.360
My life.
She said it's a failure.

06:26.400 --> 06:30.320
I don't participate; that's why
my husband won't talk to me.

06:30.370 --> 06:32.990
She's been very outspoken
since she went to Radcliffe.

06:33.030 --> 06:34.290
-(Susie sighs)
-There.

06:34.330 --> 06:36.370
What do you think?

06:36.410 --> 06:37.960
I don't know.

06:38.000 --> 06:40.040
Excuse me, is that Mermaid Ice?

06:40.080 --> 06:42.420
I'm sorry, I'm in a big hurry.
My man's coming over

06:42.460 --> 06:44.000
and I am all out
of my Mermaid Ice eye shadow.

06:44.050 --> 06:45.380
And if I am not wearing that
when he gets home,

06:45.420 --> 06:46.380
all hell breaks loose.

06:46.420 --> 06:48.550
-Really?
-You kidding?

06:48.590 --> 06:50.050
I couldn't get him
to give me the time of day,

06:50.090 --> 06:52.100
much less give me the,
you know, time of day.

06:52.140 --> 06:53.350
And then I came in here--

06:53.390 --> 06:54.680
-you remember
when I came in here? -I do.

06:54.720 --> 06:56.140
You came in here
and we talked about...

06:56.180 --> 06:58.640
I told you my life was crap,
you sold me the Mermaid Ice,

06:58.690 --> 07:01.230
and now my life
is a fat, fuzzy peach.

07:01.270 --> 07:03.730
I mean, I-I'm going broke 'cause
this stuff costs a fortune,

07:03.770 --> 07:05.070
but, man, is it worth it.

07:05.110 --> 07:06.480
-Well, my goodness.
-Yeah.

07:06.530 --> 07:08.070
If it worked for you...

07:08.110 --> 07:09.990
I'll take two.

07:10.030 --> 07:11.160
Wonderful.

07:11.200 --> 07:12.660
You will not be sorry.

07:12.700 --> 07:14.280
Margo, would you mind
ringing up Mrs. Winters

07:14.330 --> 07:16.620
while I help my return customer
over here?

07:16.660 --> 07:19.660
MARGO: Hello,
I can help you right here.

07:19.710 --> 07:21.170
Well, well, well.

07:21.210 --> 07:22.500
Just call me the closer.

07:22.540 --> 07:24.840
I'm a little surprised
to see you.

07:24.880 --> 07:28.260
Well, it's been a while
and last time we...

07:28.300 --> 07:29.760
words were said and...

07:31.550 --> 07:33.760
So, you're sorry?

07:33.800 --> 07:35.810
-Sure.
-Good.

07:35.850 --> 07:37.180
It's behind us.

07:37.220 --> 07:38.850
So, this is where
you hang out now?

07:38.890 --> 07:40.100
Well, you know
I never like to be

07:40.140 --> 07:41.640
more than three feet
from a lipstick.

07:41.690 --> 07:43.900
-I do. -It's a good job.
The girls are really nice.

07:43.940 --> 07:45.650
And there's a vending machine
in the employee break room

07:45.690 --> 07:47.860
that's broken, so if you hit it
just right, free Abba-Zabas.

07:47.900 --> 07:50.240
-Mm, you are living the dream.
-Sorry to interrupt.

07:50.280 --> 07:52.110
Midge, my parents
are making me throw them

07:52.160 --> 07:54.030
a 25th anniversary party Friday.

07:54.070 --> 07:55.830
-Friday? Short notice.
-I know.

07:55.870 --> 07:58.290
And I have no idea what people
of their age do at parties.

07:58.330 --> 08:00.040
My mom keeps saying
the word canapés.

08:00.080 --> 08:01.080
Is that an old people's dance?

08:01.120 --> 08:03.080
It's a type of hors d'œuvre.

08:03.120 --> 08:05.170
You always know everything,
so any tips would help.

08:05.210 --> 08:06.420
Hire help.

08:06.460 --> 08:07.840
-And get chairs, lots of chairs.
-Right.

08:07.880 --> 08:09.090
Old people sit.

08:09.130 --> 08:10.220
MIDGE:
And invite some of your friends

08:10.260 --> 08:11.470
for a little moral support.

08:11.510 --> 08:13.640
Who the hell would want to come
to something like this?

08:13.680 --> 08:14.970
I'll come.

08:15.010 --> 08:16.220
You will?

08:16.260 --> 08:17.310
Oh, my God, I love you.

08:17.350 --> 08:19.180
I love her.

08:19.220 --> 08:20.810
Ha.

08:20.850 --> 08:22.980
-Booked a gig.
-I'm sorry, what?

08:23.020 --> 08:24.350
It's just this thing
that I've been doing lately.

08:24.400 --> 08:25.860
I've been working
the party circuit.

08:25.900 --> 08:26.980
Which means...?

08:27.020 --> 08:28.940
I go to parties and I talk.

08:28.980 --> 08:31.400
-As opposed to...?
-People like to hear me talk.

08:31.440 --> 08:33.450
And so far, it's been young
parties, Viv's age.

08:33.490 --> 08:35.110
I haven't really worked
an older crowd yet,

08:35.159 --> 08:36.530
so this is
a perfect opportunity.

08:36.570 --> 08:38.530
I'll-I'll have to adjust
a few of my references,

08:38.580 --> 08:40.539
but you have to be able
to read an audience, right?

08:40.580 --> 08:41.960
Uh-huh.

08:42.000 --> 08:43.710
Uh, hey, are there large
quantities of narcotics

08:43.750 --> 08:44.920
in these Abba-Zabas of yours?

08:44.960 --> 08:46.210
I can't explain. I...

08:46.250 --> 08:47.710
Just-just come and you'll see.
Friday.

08:47.750 --> 08:51.130
-Oh, I can't. I have plans.
-What plans?

08:51.170 --> 08:53.970
Uh, to not be bored or miserable
at some old fuck's party.

08:54.010 --> 08:56.550
Come. You'll-you'll watch,
you'll see, you'll understand.

08:56.590 --> 08:57.800
I'll-I'll call you
with the address.

08:57.850 --> 08:59.100
Wear something... clean.

09:05.940 --> 09:07.650
ABE:
All right, everybody.

09:07.690 --> 09:09.110
Time's up.

09:09.150 --> 09:10.940
Put your papers on my desk

09:10.980 --> 09:13.320
if they contain
the correct answers,

09:13.360 --> 09:16.070
otherwise, just don't.

09:16.110 --> 09:18.570
-Abe.
-Oh, hello, Irving.

09:18.620 --> 09:19.910
What's up?

09:19.950 --> 09:21.410
I want you to meet
Charles Connelly,

09:21.450 --> 09:24.040
Executive Recruiter
from Bell Labs.

09:24.080 --> 09:25.460
Bell Labs.

09:25.500 --> 09:26.830
You got time to talk?

09:26.870 --> 09:28.710
Uh, sure.

09:28.750 --> 09:30.550
We're calling it
Project Echo, Abe.

09:30.590 --> 09:33.340
A quantum leap
in satellite technology.

09:33.380 --> 09:35.010
The commercial ramifications
of this could be huge.

09:35.050 --> 09:36.840
Not to mention
its defense capabilities.

09:36.880 --> 09:39.300
IRVING: It would revolutionize
the communications industry.

09:39.350 --> 09:40.970
CHARLES: And Bell Labs
is leading the pack.

09:41.010 --> 09:42.310
Abe, we're gathering
the best and the brightest

09:42.350 --> 09:43.770
to help us get there first.

09:43.810 --> 09:46.140
-May I stop you there?
-CHARLES: Of course.

09:46.190 --> 09:49.230
I want no part of Sputnik panic.

09:49.270 --> 09:50.440
This smacks of that.

09:50.480 --> 09:52.030
There's no panic, Abe.

09:52.070 --> 09:53.110
We're doing this right.

09:53.150 --> 09:54.320
We never rush R&D.

09:54.360 --> 09:55.400
Your colleague, Bill Chernik...

09:55.450 --> 09:56.780
Bill and Abe have known
each other a long time.

09:56.820 --> 09:58.870
Bill Chernik's a good man.

09:58.910 --> 10:00.450
CHARLES: He's been consulting
with us for a while.

10:00.490 --> 10:02.240
Ask him about us.
You'll like what you hear.

10:02.290 --> 10:03.950
There's no way this could work.

10:04.000 --> 10:05.870
My class load is so full.

10:05.910 --> 10:07.920
We can help with that.
Take things off your plate.

10:07.960 --> 10:10.340
No, I'm loath to do that.

10:10.380 --> 10:11.920
CHARLES:
We'll work around your schedule.

10:11.960 --> 10:13.710
An applied mathematician
of your skills

10:13.760 --> 10:15.340
is in high demand these days.

10:15.380 --> 10:17.220
-We need you.
-(chuckles)

10:17.260 --> 10:19.010
I told you he'd be a tough sell.

10:19.050 --> 10:20.600
Which makes us want you more.

10:20.640 --> 10:21.890
Pending a security clearance,

10:21.930 --> 10:23.310
Bell Labs is
at your beck and call.

10:23.350 --> 10:24.350
I need to get home.

10:24.390 --> 10:25.980
Let me walk with you.

10:26.020 --> 10:27.600
-(bell tolls)
-Please think it over.

10:27.640 --> 10:29.650
Take some time.
And call with any questions.

10:29.690 --> 10:31.440
-I doubt I'll have any.
-Call anyhow.

10:31.480 --> 10:33.110
I'll give you the pitch
all over again.

10:33.150 --> 10:35.190
And thanks for your time.

10:35.230 --> 10:36.900
See you Monday, Abe.

10:39.910 --> 10:42.240
We're going out to dinner!

10:42.280 --> 10:43.410
ROSE:
Abe?

10:43.450 --> 10:45.910
Rose, Rose, get in here.

10:45.950 --> 10:47.910
We are going out to dinner.

10:47.960 --> 10:51.000
Ruby Foo's, Le Pavillon,
name it.

10:51.040 --> 10:53.040
Abe, slow down.
Why are we going out to dinner?

10:53.090 --> 10:54.710
Bell Labs, Rose.

10:54.750 --> 10:56.840
I got an offer to work
at Bell Labs.

10:56.880 --> 10:58.930
-What?
-Bell Labs down in the village!

10:58.970 --> 11:00.390
Oh, my God, Abe!

11:00.430 --> 11:03.510
-(laughing)
-Oh, oh.

11:03.550 --> 11:06.680
You should have seen me
with that recruiter.

11:06.720 --> 11:08.770
I played it so cool.

11:08.810 --> 11:10.810
I kind of nodded like this,

11:10.850 --> 11:12.270
was shaking my head
a little bit.

11:12.310 --> 11:13.900
Very serious, very dubious.

11:13.940 --> 11:16.570
-Oh, you can look
extremely dubious. -(laughs)

11:16.610 --> 11:18.900
And he was eating
out of the palm of my hand.

11:18.950 --> 11:21.110
This is the big leagues, Rose.

11:21.160 --> 11:24.660
This... this is
the hotbed of invention.

11:24.700 --> 11:27.580
That TV that you all
like so much,

11:27.620 --> 11:31.250
-courtesy of Bell Labs
transistor work. -No.

11:31.290 --> 11:33.460
-ETHAN: Grandpa,
I was watching that. -Oh.

11:33.500 --> 11:37.960
Bardeen and Brattain and
Shockley won a Nobel for that.

11:38.010 --> 11:40.050
And now I am in their ranks.

11:40.090 --> 11:41.760
Where are we going for dinner?

11:41.800 --> 11:43.180
What about a dinner?

11:43.220 --> 11:44.600
We're going out.
The whole family.

11:44.640 --> 11:45.890
Call Noah and Astrid.

11:45.930 --> 11:48.720
He's got an offer
from Bell Labs.

11:48.770 --> 11:51.100
-Wow, Papa, congratulations.
-(laughs)

11:51.140 --> 11:52.690
Thank you very much.

11:52.730 --> 11:54.190
You've been obsessing
on Bell Labs

11:54.230 --> 11:55.820
-for, like, 20 years now.
-Mm-hmm.

11:55.860 --> 11:57.230
I haven't been obsessing
on them.

11:57.280 --> 11:59.110
My whole childhood, it was Bell
Labs this and Bell Labs that,

11:59.150 --> 12:00.780
and, "My God,
I'd give up pastrami

12:00.820 --> 12:02.030
for a job at Bell Labs."

12:02.070 --> 12:03.360
(laughs)
I may have mentioned them.

12:03.410 --> 12:04.910
A-And once a year, we'd tour
the building? The outside,

12:04.950 --> 12:06.280
-because we weren't allowed in.
-You kids would play

12:06.330 --> 12:07.950
on the sidewalk while your
father would jump up and down,

12:07.990 --> 12:09.290
-and try and peek
in the windows. -Yes.

12:09.330 --> 12:11.330
That may have happened
once or twice.

12:11.370 --> 12:13.000
-(chuckles)
-Is that my blouse?

12:13.040 --> 12:15.130
-Uh, yes, but it's not
quite right. -For what?

12:15.170 --> 12:18.250
Okay, I-I'm talking about
very important things here,

12:18.300 --> 12:20.170
and you're talking
about clothes.

12:20.210 --> 12:23.590
I have to get dressed.
Congratulations, Papa.

12:23.630 --> 12:25.890
How often do I get
a job at Bell Labs

12:25.930 --> 12:28.720
and no one wants
to celebrate with me?

12:28.760 --> 12:31.600
Oh, Abe, my love, we will find
the perfect night to celebrate.

12:31.640 --> 12:33.140
With Noah and Astrid?

12:33.190 --> 12:34.350
Uh, they will be there.

12:34.400 --> 12:35.770
I mean, it's Bell Labs.

12:35.810 --> 12:38.480
And we, we are all
so very proud of you.

12:38.520 --> 12:40.030
Mama, where's your green dress?

12:40.070 --> 12:41.030
At the cleaners.

12:41.070 --> 12:42.530
(whispers):
Oh, shoot.

12:45.660 --> 12:47.780
I'm never sure
about me and peach.

12:47.830 --> 12:50.450
Hmm. I am.

12:52.540 --> 12:53.710
Here.

12:53.750 --> 12:54.830
The Dior?

12:54.870 --> 12:56.460
Oh, that's perfect.

12:56.500 --> 13:00.250
-So, you're going
to another party. -Hmm?

13:00.300 --> 13:02.380
That's the fourth one
this week, isn't it?

13:02.420 --> 13:04.510
Four this week, three last week.

13:04.550 --> 13:05.970
Which, of course,
means they've already seen

13:06.010 --> 13:07.180
everything in my closet.

13:07.220 --> 13:08.720
Enter yours.

13:08.760 --> 13:12.560
So, are these friends
of yours and Joel's?

13:12.600 --> 13:14.560
No. New friends.

13:14.600 --> 13:15.940
-Girls from work.
-Hmm.

13:15.980 --> 13:17.400
What do you think?

13:17.440 --> 13:19.570
Lovely, understated.

13:19.610 --> 13:21.070
-Understated?
-Mm-hmm.

13:21.110 --> 13:23.570
-Next. -You don't want
to be understated?

13:23.610 --> 13:24.860
MIDGE:
I need to stand out.

13:24.900 --> 13:26.280
ROSE:
Well, you always stand out.

13:26.320 --> 13:28.160
I need to stand out
in a very specific way.

13:28.200 --> 13:29.530
Well, you could wear nothing.

13:29.580 --> 13:31.160
That would get
some sort of attention.

13:31.200 --> 13:32.500
Don't I know it.

13:32.540 --> 13:33.540
Now, tell me about--

13:33.580 --> 13:35.120
not until my funeral.

13:35.160 --> 13:39.500
So tell me, are there men
at these, uh, parties?

13:39.540 --> 13:41.550
They aren't nun parties, Mama.

13:41.590 --> 13:43.840
Well, you know, a girl
standing alone at a party

13:43.880 --> 13:45.590
-says just one thing.
-What's that?

13:45.630 --> 13:47.010
-I'm prey. Hunt me.
-Perfect.

13:47.050 --> 13:48.590
-Miriam.
-No, seriously,

13:48.640 --> 13:50.350
I was looking
for a catchphrase. That's it.

13:50.390 --> 13:51.760
You should wait
to go to these parties.

13:51.810 --> 13:52.970
It's too soon.

13:53.020 --> 13:54.350
I'll add some gloves to this.

13:54.390 --> 13:55.770
That should give it some zazz.

13:55.810 --> 13:57.400
-Miriam...
-Thanks for the dress, Mama.

13:57.440 --> 13:59.400
ROSE:
Oh...

14:07.860 --> 14:09.030
What are you doing here?

14:09.070 --> 14:10.320
What am I...?

14:10.370 --> 14:11.910
Y-You invited me
to this stupid party.

14:11.950 --> 14:12.990
No, I mean on the elevator.

14:13.040 --> 14:14.660
You're not leaving, are you?

14:14.700 --> 14:16.500
No, I've been riding this thing
up and down for an hour

14:16.540 --> 14:17.960
waiting for you to float in here

14:18.000 --> 14:19.630
on your golden fucking
Icarus horse.

14:19.670 --> 14:21.170
You got a pretty loose concept
of time, lady.

14:21.210 --> 14:22.800
Cabs were scarce.

14:22.840 --> 14:24.260
Well, are you waiting
for an engraved invitation?

14:24.300 --> 14:25.510
Get in here.

14:28.180 --> 14:29.930
Got to know
the building pretty well.

14:29.970 --> 14:31.550
Old guy on six has cancer.

14:31.600 --> 14:32.970
Oh, that's terrible.

14:33.010 --> 14:34.850
I inspired him to reach out
to his daughter.

14:34.890 --> 14:36.430
They've been on the outs
since she divorced.

14:36.480 --> 14:37.690
She's here now, cooking for him.

14:37.730 --> 14:38.810
That's nice.

14:38.850 --> 14:40.520
Oh, you hear that?

14:40.560 --> 14:42.320
Couple on the fourth floor,
they've been fighting

14:42.360 --> 14:43.820
for a full half hour.

14:43.860 --> 14:45.860
He pinched some girl's ass,
she saw.

14:45.900 --> 14:47.950
May have been
the cancer guy's daughter.

14:47.990 --> 14:50.200
Oh, I hope she did nothing
to encourage that.

14:50.240 --> 14:51.280
(elevator bell dings)

14:51.320 --> 14:52.410
You look nice, by the way.

14:52.450 --> 14:53.530
Thanks.

14:53.580 --> 14:54.790
Clean shirt?

14:54.830 --> 14:56.370
Uh, define "clean."

14:56.410 --> 14:59.580
(indistinct chatter,
soft music playing)

14:59.620 --> 15:02.210
Okay, this is the worst party
I've ever been to.

15:02.250 --> 15:04.590
We just walked in the door.

15:04.630 --> 15:06.260
Let's go get a hot dog
or something.

15:06.300 --> 15:08.510
No, no, no, stay.

15:08.550 --> 15:10.180
-Midge, hi.
-Hi, Mary.

15:10.220 --> 15:12.010
This is my friend, Susie.
Susie, Mary.

15:12.050 --> 15:14.180
Hi, Susie, come on in.
Meet the others.

15:14.220 --> 15:15.810
Eh, I feel like I got it.

15:15.850 --> 15:16.930
I'll see you inside, Mary.

15:16.970 --> 15:19.560
Nice meeting you.

15:19.600 --> 15:21.730
-What a drip.
-You're the drip.

15:21.770 --> 15:23.520
Come on, get with
the program here.

15:23.560 --> 15:25.940
Why would anyone in their
right mind go to parties?

15:25.980 --> 15:27.740
I mean, just buy
some Sno Balls and a beer,

15:27.780 --> 15:30.450
and take the subway at
rush hour, same fucking thing.

15:30.490 --> 15:32.280
I-I'm sorry,
I just don't get it.

15:32.320 --> 15:34.330
Midge, I think I'm in love.

15:34.370 --> 15:36.990
-Not again. -Come see him,
tell me if I'm crazy.

15:37.040 --> 15:38.120
He's my dad's boss.

15:38.160 --> 15:39.620
He's 70.

15:39.660 --> 15:41.870
And deaf and married,
but keep an open mind.

15:41.920 --> 15:43.290
That's my cue.

15:43.330 --> 15:44.500
Huh?

15:44.540 --> 15:46.710
(applause)

15:48.420 --> 15:50.420
Wait a minute.

15:51.470 --> 15:54.930
Wait a minute.

15:54.970 --> 15:57.060
I get it. I get it.

15:57.100 --> 15:59.180
Mary? I get it.

15:59.230 --> 16:00.850
MIDGE:
Wow, your silver anniversary.

16:00.890 --> 16:02.560
Your husband looks thrilled.

16:02.600 --> 16:05.940
Maybe we do need a better
motivator for men

16:05.980 --> 16:08.400
to get them to care
about the silver anniversary.

16:08.440 --> 16:10.320
Because what man really cares
about silver?

16:10.360 --> 16:13.910
Maybe 25 years is the Yankees
season tickets anniversary.

16:13.950 --> 16:15.870
-(laughter)
-Yeah!

16:15.910 --> 16:17.540
Yeah, and then
to get them to 50,

16:17.580 --> 16:19.290
we need something really good.

16:19.330 --> 16:21.660
Maybe it's the "another
woman's boobs" anniversary.

16:21.710 --> 16:23.790
-(laughter)
-Mm-hmm.

16:23.830 --> 16:27.630
Me, personally, I-I was never
great at gift-giving.

16:27.670 --> 16:30.460
Maybe it's because I never
got to celebrate Christmas.

16:30.510 --> 16:32.470
-I got Hanukkah.
-(soft laughter)

16:32.510 --> 16:34.180
Doesn't exactly prepare you
the same way.

16:34.220 --> 16:36.300
For Christmas,
a gentile would get a bike

16:36.350 --> 16:38.430
as a reminder
that their parents love them.

16:38.470 --> 16:40.890
For Hanukkah, we would get socks

16:40.930 --> 16:43.100
as a reminder
that we were persecuted.

16:43.140 --> 16:45.060
(laughter)

16:46.610 --> 16:48.520
Hey. You look happy.

16:48.570 --> 16:49.650
As a clam.

16:49.690 --> 16:50.940
I ate all the clams, by the way.

16:50.990 --> 16:52.490
See? Parties aren't so bad.

16:52.530 --> 16:54.200
Hmm. I'm just trying to
figure out the best way

16:54.240 --> 16:55.780
to hide a lobster under my hat.

16:55.820 --> 16:57.740
-So, did you catch my set?
-Your what?

16:57.780 --> 16:59.620
Just now. You hear all
the laughs I got?

16:59.660 --> 17:01.000
Yeah, I heard the laughs.

17:01.040 --> 17:02.160
Pretty funny, right?

17:02.200 --> 17:03.330
You're a funny woman.

17:03.370 --> 17:04.920
Could you pass the asparagus?

17:04.960 --> 17:07.380
I did a version of the Hanukkah
run a couple weeks ago,

17:07.420 --> 17:09.040
but I've honed it
a lot since then.

17:09.089 --> 17:11.010
Yeah, that was some
top-notch honing, there.

17:11.050 --> 17:13.300
RANDALL:
Darling? Darling, over here!

17:13.339 --> 17:14.970
Uh, yes, dear?

17:15.010 --> 17:16.390
RANDALL:
Come over here by the window.

17:16.430 --> 17:19.050
You're gonna want to see this.

17:19.099 --> 17:20.930
-MAN: Shh.
-What am I looking at?

17:20.970 --> 17:22.849
Well, nothing, silly,
the curtains are closed.

17:22.890 --> 17:24.640
I'm incorrigible.

17:24.690 --> 17:26.480
Let's open the curtains here.

17:26.520 --> 17:28.020
There, see?

17:28.060 --> 17:29.520
It's the neighbors
across the way again.

17:29.570 --> 17:30.980
The wife just got home.

17:31.030 --> 17:32.740
She's taking off her coat,

17:32.780 --> 17:34.530
and here comes her husband
to say hello,

17:34.570 --> 17:35.700
-and-- oh!
-(gasps)

17:35.740 --> 17:36.860
Did you see that?

17:36.910 --> 17:38.200
-He fell hard.
-(laughter)

17:38.240 --> 17:40.030
What the heck did he slip on?

17:40.080 --> 17:41.620
Whatever it is,
he's picking it up.

17:41.660 --> 17:44.290
It looks like a towel-- nope,
it's the cat.

17:44.330 --> 17:46.250
-He slipped on the cat?
-MIDGE: And he is angry.

17:46.290 --> 17:47.460
RANDALL:
The cat or the man?

17:47.500 --> 17:48.670
MIDGE: Well, they're both
pretty verklempt.

17:48.710 --> 17:50.340
Oh, you're Jewish.
I never knew that.

17:50.380 --> 17:52.130
20 years of marriage
and we're still learning things

17:52.170 --> 17:54.170
-about each other.
-I like that about us.

17:54.220 --> 17:55.930
RANDALL:
He's struggling with the cat...

17:55.970 --> 17:58.510
-The cat knocked his toupee off!
-MIDGE: The cat did him a favor.

17:58.550 --> 17:59.970
RANDALL: And he's thrown
the cat out the window.

18:00.010 --> 18:01.510
-MIDGE: Oh, my God!
-(laughter)

18:01.560 --> 18:02.720
MAN (on TV):
And the car had to have

18:02.770 --> 18:04.100
a fancy garage and a fancy
mansion to go with it.

18:04.140 --> 18:06.140
WOMAN (on TV): But I didn't
expect you to get the money

18:06.190 --> 18:07.900
-this month. -MAN: He wouldn't
care where I get it from!

18:07.940 --> 18:10.560
(woman continues speaking
indistinctly on TV)

18:10.610 --> 18:12.820
I told you to get it
and get out of that.

18:12.860 --> 18:15.070
ROSE:
Poor Virginia.

18:15.110 --> 18:17.700
Peter never listens to her,
now look at the mess he's in.

18:17.740 --> 18:20.120
Men only hear men...
and bartenders.

18:20.160 --> 18:22.660
She really thinks getting angry
will work?

18:22.700 --> 18:25.370
Why don't these writers just
give her a boyfriend, or a gun?

18:25.410 --> 18:27.210
-My God. So hostile today.
-I'm sorry.

18:27.250 --> 18:28.670
I'm just a wreck right now.

18:28.710 --> 18:30.290
-Everything's falling apart.
-Hold it.

18:30.330 --> 18:32.290
MAN (on TV): What's the
best way to reduce?

18:32.340 --> 18:34.300
-Commercial. -Eat plenty?
Or starve yourself?

18:34.340 --> 18:35.510
A half-empty...

18:35.550 --> 18:37.630
Okay.

18:37.680 --> 18:39.890
Miriam stopped wearing
her wedding ring.

18:39.930 --> 18:41.550
Oh, we're gonna need the ball.

18:41.600 --> 18:43.350
And Joel moved in
with that girlfriend.

18:43.390 --> 18:45.100
-DRINA: The secretary.
-ROSE: The home-wrecker.

18:45.140 --> 18:46.600
Like Sasha from
Edge of Night,

18:46.640 --> 18:48.140
always spreading it around.

18:48.190 --> 18:49.810
She's a nothing.
I know it won't last.

18:49.850 --> 18:51.310
If the secretary were just
out of the picture,

18:51.360 --> 18:52.690
Joel would come back.

18:52.730 --> 18:54.230
You want her out of the picture?

18:54.280 --> 18:56.070
I have cousins.
They have skills.

18:56.110 --> 18:58.030
-I'm sorry?
-Nothing.

18:58.070 --> 19:00.110
I'm looking at the ball.

19:00.160 --> 19:02.030
I see a new man
walking toward Miriam.

19:02.070 --> 19:03.490
Oh, my God, no.

19:03.530 --> 19:05.410
But he walked right past.
Yes, he's gone.

19:05.450 --> 19:06.870
-Feel better?
-It doesn't matter.

19:06.910 --> 19:08.250
There'll be another man
and another

19:08.290 --> 19:10.040
and another;
she's on the prowl.

19:10.080 --> 19:12.710
Every night she gets all dolled
up and goes to these parties.

19:12.750 --> 19:15.800
Like she's given up on Joel
and is trolling for husbands.

19:15.840 --> 19:17.300
She doesn't understand.

19:17.340 --> 19:18.880
Being a divorcée
is terrible, yes,

19:18.920 --> 19:20.380
but being on your
second marriage is...

19:20.430 --> 19:21.970
-Worse.
-So much worse.

19:22.010 --> 19:23.640
Second marriage says failure.

19:23.680 --> 19:25.970
At least divorcée
sounds continental.

19:26.020 --> 19:28.100
It'd be better if Joel had died,
then she'd be a widow.

19:28.140 --> 19:29.640
At least there's dignity
in that.

19:29.690 --> 19:31.020
You want Joel to die?

19:31.060 --> 19:32.810
Again, with the cousins.

19:32.860 --> 19:35.360
-I don't understand.
-Okay, I give up.

19:35.400 --> 19:37.780
I see an open path for Miriam.

19:37.820 --> 19:39.990
She will find her way.
I promise.

19:40.030 --> 19:42.410
Tell you what,
I'll make a tonic.

19:42.450 --> 19:45.530
Pour it in her soup,
it will help the luck stick.

19:45.580 --> 19:48.080
-Thank you, DRINA.
-You still look worried.

19:48.120 --> 19:50.000
-(sighs)
-I have the perfect thing.

19:50.040 --> 19:51.370
A distraction.

19:54.920 --> 19:57.210
♪ ♪

19:57.250 --> 19:59.260
Shh, shh.

20:01.300 --> 20:03.840
I think you'll love the color,
Mrs. Maracek. See you again.

20:06.260 --> 20:07.810
And what color
would you recommend

20:07.850 --> 20:09.850
for my unique complexion, Miss?

20:09.890 --> 20:11.480
Pasty?
I'd recommend Spackle.

20:11.520 --> 20:13.100
-And a putty knife.
-I'll pass.

20:13.150 --> 20:15.060
-So what are you doing here?
-I have a proposition.

20:15.110 --> 20:16.610
Oh, blessed day.

20:16.650 --> 20:17.820
The ring department's
on the third floor.

20:17.860 --> 20:18.940
Remember the four "C"s.

20:18.980 --> 20:20.240
A business proposition.

20:20.280 --> 20:21.400
But not here.

20:21.450 --> 20:22.570
You have time later today?

20:22.610 --> 20:24.370
I'm off in an hour.

20:24.410 --> 20:26.160
-Can you meet me at
the Stage Deli? -Sure.

20:26.200 --> 20:27.620
Great.

20:27.660 --> 20:29.790
Point me to the
shoplifting department?

20:29.830 --> 20:31.830
-Second floor, south side.
-Oh.

20:31.870 --> 20:33.960
-Excellent service.
-Oh.

20:34.000 --> 20:36.000
(indistinct chatter)

20:38.000 --> 20:44.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

20:45.010 --> 20:46.510
Oh. Hello there.

20:46.550 --> 20:48.510
Midge, this is my karate
instructor, Lew Fogelman.

20:48.560 --> 20:50.100
I'm Randall's agent.

20:50.140 --> 20:52.270
He's with William Morris,
so look impressed.

20:52.310 --> 20:53.890
I am impressed.

20:53.940 --> 20:55.310
Midge Maisel.

20:55.350 --> 20:56.730
I've heard good things.

20:56.770 --> 20:58.110
-I like you already.
-(chuckles)

20:58.150 --> 21:00.360
We're sitting now.

21:00.400 --> 21:03.070
So... my boy told me he was
having a bite with you,

21:03.110 --> 21:04.490
and I was in the neighborhood.

21:04.530 --> 21:06.200
Hope you don't mind
my stopping by.

21:06.240 --> 21:08.200
The Stage Deli is open to all.

21:08.240 --> 21:09.700
He's headed toward great things,
this one.

21:09.740 --> 21:11.200
-Just not in entertainment.
-Oh, will you shut up?

21:11.250 --> 21:12.580
You're annoying us both.

21:12.620 --> 21:13.830
I'm winningly self-deprecating.

21:13.870 --> 21:15.420
It says so right there
on the new resumes

21:15.460 --> 21:17.630
-you made me pony up for.
-Anyhow, he mentioned

21:17.670 --> 21:19.380
that the two of you have been
teaming up lately,

21:19.420 --> 21:20.670
which I find very interesting.

21:20.710 --> 21:22.970
-Teaming up?
-Just at parties.

21:23.010 --> 21:24.550
Just for fun. However,

21:24.590 --> 21:27.050
have you ever thought about
doing it professionally?

21:27.090 --> 21:29.720
-I-I don't understand.
-Sometimes a charming, funny guy

21:29.760 --> 21:32.980
with a cute, dizzy broad
on his arm is a good sell.

21:33.020 --> 21:35.020
-And I'm the dizzy broad?
-Fine.

21:35.060 --> 21:37.270
I'll be the dizzy broad and
you be the charming, funny guy.

21:37.310 --> 21:38.860
MIDGE:
Perfect.

21:38.900 --> 21:40.440
So you want to do an act...
with me?

21:40.480 --> 21:42.570
They're always looking
for duos like us

21:42.610 --> 21:44.740
for commercials,
radio, industrials.

21:44.780 --> 21:46.410
Company events--
you tell a few jokes,

21:46.450 --> 21:47.870
you mention the product
a bunch of times,

21:47.910 --> 21:49.200
you look pretty.

21:49.240 --> 21:50.950
You can make decent money
at this.

21:50.990 --> 21:53.540
-Seriously? -RANDALL: We'd be
a booker's dream.

21:53.580 --> 21:55.910
Who knows, we may be the next
Nichols and May.

21:57.420 --> 21:59.380
-You don't know Nichols and May?
-Should I?

21:59.420 --> 22:01.710
The next time they're in town,
you're going.

22:01.750 --> 22:03.130
-We're going.
-LEW: Speaking of going,

22:03.170 --> 22:04.800
