coarse and crude.

23:51.570 --> 23:52.700
Randall is totally legit.

23:52.740 --> 23:54.320
I met his agent and everything.

23:54.370 --> 23:56.330
You-you met his agent?

23:56.370 --> 23:57.950
At the Stage Deli.

23:58.000 --> 24:00.290
Uh, Lew something,
from William Morris.

24:00.330 --> 24:02.120
Nice guy. Bought us lunch.

24:02.170 --> 24:03.750
Susie, toilet's broken again.

24:03.790 --> 24:06.800
You might want to send
the house manager to manage it.

24:06.840 --> 24:08.300
You did that on purpose.

24:08.340 --> 24:09.550
Look, I got to go.

24:09.590 --> 24:11.550
Good luck with the Buicks.

24:15.680 --> 24:17.310
I can't find my cuff links.

24:17.350 --> 24:19.100
Did you check your cuffs, Papa?

24:19.140 --> 24:21.850
These are my Gimbels' cuff
links, my everyday cuff links.

24:21.890 --> 24:24.400
-I need my Finchley cuff links.
-Abe, you look fabulous

24:24.440 --> 24:26.440
-without them. Oh...
-It's a Finchley night.

24:26.480 --> 24:28.030
I'm gonna check the kids' room.

24:28.070 --> 24:30.030
The kids do not have
your Finchley cuff links.

24:30.070 --> 24:31.900
I had cuff links,
your kids moved in,

24:31.950 --> 24:33.200
-I don't have cuff links.
-Mm.

24:33.240 --> 24:34.530
Draw a conclusion.

24:34.570 --> 24:36.410
Shalom! It's Astrid!

24:36.450 --> 24:39.540
-Come on in, Astrid.
-Oh, hi! (giggles)

24:39.580 --> 24:40.830
Hello, you.

24:40.870 --> 24:42.120
-Mwah!
-Where's Noah?

24:42.160 --> 24:43.920
Astrid, please
let me stop the car

24:43.960 --> 24:45.580
-before you get out.
-I'm sorry.

24:45.630 --> 24:47.500
-We discussed this.
-I couldn't help it.

24:47.540 --> 24:49.500
I-I got presents
from our trip to Israel.

24:49.550 --> 24:51.720
Where are Esther and Ethan?
Where are my little pishers?

24:51.760 --> 24:53.470
Oh, they're already
at the babysitter's.

24:53.510 --> 24:56.090
-Oh, no. -Don't worry,
she tends to bring them back.

24:56.140 --> 24:58.760
-No cuff links. -Oh, you're
looking very handsome, Abe.

24:58.810 --> 25:00.720
I might as well be naked.

25:00.770 --> 25:02.180
That's an image
we're all happy to have.

25:02.230 --> 25:04.230
Pop, I got my hands
on the Bell Labs schematics

25:04.270 --> 25:06.100
from a friend--
lots of info, tons of specs.

25:06.150 --> 25:07.270
Study. Now.

25:07.310 --> 25:08.820
He walks right past his mother?

25:08.860 --> 25:11.400
-Sorry, Ma. Good to see you.
Mwah. Mwah. -Mwah.

25:11.440 --> 25:12.900
Midget, good to see you, too.

25:12.950 --> 25:14.780
Eh. You I could take or leave.

25:14.820 --> 25:16.620
Really, Astrid,
my arms are getting tired.

25:16.660 --> 25:18.490
-Please put those down.
-It's just that your apartment's

25:18.530 --> 25:20.120
so beautiful,
and I know you like everything

25:20.160 --> 25:22.250
in a certain way,
so maybe Noah can just take them

25:22.290 --> 25:24.210
back to the car
until the kids get home, or...

25:24.250 --> 25:25.870
-Give this to me.
-Oh, thank you.

25:25.920 --> 25:27.380
What's in the bag?

25:27.420 --> 25:28.710
Gefilte fish.

25:28.750 --> 25:31.260
-My next guess.
-I tried a new recipe.

25:31.300 --> 25:34.130
You'll be very happy-- there are
no onions in this one, Rose.

25:34.170 --> 25:36.010
"Happy" doesn't
quite describe it.

25:36.050 --> 25:37.930
-I'll take it, ma'am.
-Thank you, Zelda.

25:37.970 --> 25:39.930
-You know where to...
-Yes, I do.

25:39.970 --> 25:41.600
(sighs):
Here. This is for you.

25:41.640 --> 25:43.680
Honestly, Astrid,
you don't have to bring us gifts

25:43.730 --> 25:45.350
every time you go to Israel.

25:45.390 --> 25:47.730
-I... -What was this,
your sixth, seventh trip?

25:47.770 --> 25:49.110
-11th. (giggles)
-MIDGE: Oh.

25:49.150 --> 25:52.150
Can't get enough
of the Holy Land.

25:52.190 --> 25:55.240
(Abe and Noah talking
in distance)

25:55.280 --> 25:58.950
-What a beautiful mezuzah.
-(Astrid laughs)

25:58.990 --> 26:01.620
I'd never seen one
that big before. (laughs)

26:01.660 --> 26:03.950
It looks like it ate
all the other mezuzahs.

26:04.000 --> 26:05.290
Is that bad?

26:05.330 --> 26:07.420
-Oh. No.
-I could return it.

26:07.460 --> 26:10.290
-To Israel? -Rose,
Bell Labs has two cafeterias.

26:10.340 --> 26:12.050
Different cuisines in each one.

26:12.090 --> 26:13.920
I can choose.
I get to choose.

26:13.960 --> 26:15.590
I better start easing them out,

26:15.630 --> 26:17.470
or they'll lose all interest
in dinner.

26:18.510 --> 26:20.510
I brought you a gift, too.

26:20.550 --> 26:22.560
Is it another giant mezuzah?

26:22.600 --> 26:24.560
Oh, it is such a stupid gift.

26:24.600 --> 26:26.560
-Astrid, no.
-No, Rose has a mezuzah.

26:26.600 --> 26:28.650
You have a mezuzah.
It's not shoes--

26:28.690 --> 26:30.770
you can't just change them out
every season.

26:30.810 --> 26:33.280
No, but if we ever move
to a very big house...

26:33.320 --> 26:35.280
Oh, I just wish Rose liked me.

26:35.320 --> 26:37.530
She likes you very much.
She loves you, Astrid.

26:37.570 --> 26:39.490
-I make her nervous.
-Breathing makes her nervous.

26:39.530 --> 26:41.240
I thought that converting
would help.

26:41.280 --> 26:43.540
I know that it's hard having
an outsider in your family.

26:43.580 --> 26:45.330
You are not an outsider.

26:45.370 --> 26:47.250
-Mm-mm. I heard comments at
our wedding. -No one commented.

26:47.290 --> 26:49.000
"What's up with the shiksa
Noah married?"

26:49.040 --> 26:52.210
-Aunt Gertie, once.
-I'm an outsider. I'm barren.

26:52.250 --> 26:53.340
Astrid, you're young.

26:53.380 --> 26:55.050
No, I'm not. I'm 30.

26:55.090 --> 26:56.670
We're seeing the fertility
doctor again tomorrow.

26:56.720 --> 26:59.840
He's one of the pioneers
in cervical cap inseminations.

26:59.890 --> 27:01.300
Well, everyone looks good
in a cap.

27:01.350 --> 27:02.760
I'm almost too afraid to go.

27:02.800 --> 27:04.810
I mean, what if it
doesn't work this time?

27:04.850 --> 27:07.100
What methods did you and Joel
use to get pregnant?

27:07.140 --> 27:09.690
Well... sex.

27:09.730 --> 27:13.020
Yeah, that seems to work
for most people.

27:13.070 --> 27:14.110
Oh, honey...

27:14.150 --> 27:15.400
Seven years of trying.
I mean,

27:15.440 --> 27:16.690
(whispers):
what if he leaves me?

27:16.740 --> 27:18.150
Noah is not going to leave you.

27:18.200 --> 27:20.860
You did everything perfectly,
and that yutz left you.

27:20.910 --> 27:22.570
Noah loves you.

27:22.620 --> 27:24.330
And I know you think
he's pretty dreamy,

27:24.370 --> 27:26.700
but I'm his sister,
so I can tell you the truth.

27:26.750 --> 27:29.830
-Oh. -He's a big nerd
who lucked out and married up.

27:29.870 --> 27:31.830
-(sighs): No.
-Seriously. You're saving him

27:31.880 --> 27:34.250
-from a sad, lonely life
in a lab. -(laughs)

27:34.290 --> 27:36.000
He's not going anywhere. Okay?

27:36.050 --> 27:38.800
-ROSE: Miriam! Astrid!
We're leaving! -Okay.

27:38.840 --> 27:40.260
Okay.

27:40.300 --> 27:42.680
(indistinct chatter continues
in distance)

27:48.140 --> 27:51.900
♪ ♪

27:51.940 --> 27:54.110
ABE:
This is the eighth grade,

27:54.150 --> 27:56.150
and Miss Bedetsky
is so overloaded

27:56.190 --> 27:57.940
with math homework to grade,

27:57.980 --> 27:58.990
I offered to help.

27:59.030 --> 28:00.530
I was new to her class,

28:00.570 --> 28:01.910
and she thought it was cute

28:01.950 --> 28:04.070
that a 13-year-old
would offer to help.

28:04.120 --> 28:06.030
The emphasis on education
in the Jewish faith

28:06.080 --> 28:08.950
may be the thing
that I admire the most.

28:09.000 --> 28:10.750
Anyway, she let me try.

28:10.790 --> 28:12.870
And I graded them perfectly--

28:12.920 --> 28:15.000
without even using the key.

28:15.040 --> 28:18.000
She looked at me, astonished,
and then said,

28:18.050 --> 28:20.920
"Abraham Weissman,
you are a natural born

28:20.970 --> 28:22.590
-mathematician."
-Mm.

28:22.630 --> 28:23.840
I was so proud.

28:23.890 --> 28:25.850
(laughs)
Did you stay in touch with her?

28:25.890 --> 28:27.430
-That moron? No.
-ROSE: Abe.

28:27.470 --> 28:29.640
What? There were mistakes
she didn't find

28:29.680 --> 28:31.560
in the papers
she graded that day.

28:31.600 --> 28:33.100
So I corrected them
and immediately transferred

28:33.150 --> 28:34.900
-out of her class.
-He couldn't just stop

28:34.940 --> 28:36.900
at the nice part--
he just, he had to keep going.

28:36.940 --> 28:39.360
She left the school after that,
on my recommendation.

28:39.400 --> 28:41.400
I would like to propose a toast.
(clears throat)

28:41.450 --> 28:43.490
-ASTRID: Mmm.
-I have never understood

28:43.530 --> 28:46.320
what Abe Weissman was
talking about ever in my life.

28:46.370 --> 28:48.620
One time I made the mistake
of asking about his day.

28:48.660 --> 28:50.080
45 minutes later,
he was still talking,

28:50.120 --> 28:51.620
but I had taken to my bed.

28:51.660 --> 28:53.790
-(laughing)
-So for both of our sakes,

28:53.830 --> 28:55.830
I'm very glad
that he's finally found

28:55.880 --> 28:58.340
some people
who truly speak his language.

28:58.380 --> 29:01.340
And apparently whatever he's
been saying is very impressive.

29:01.380 --> 29:04.340
So please join me
in toasting my father,

29:04.380 --> 29:07.180
-the great Abe Weissman.
-NOAH: Cheers.

29:07.220 --> 29:09.140
L'chaim!

29:09.180 --> 29:11.020
(Midge clears throat)

29:22.360 --> 29:24.950
-What do we do?
-We should leave.

29:24.990 --> 29:27.030
-We're not leaving.
-He's practically on top of us.

29:27.070 --> 29:28.030
Wait, is that the secretary?

29:28.070 --> 29:29.120
There are a thousand restaurants

29:29.160 --> 29:30.580
in the city--
what are the odds?

29:30.620 --> 29:31.750
One in sixteen thousand,
four hundred fifty...

29:31.790 --> 29:33.040
Twelve thousand,
three hundred...

29:33.080 --> 29:34.660
I'm taking into account
weather effects,

29:34.710 --> 29:36.330
that some restaurants
are closed on Mondays...

29:36.370 --> 29:37.920
Yeah, yeah, but I'm calculating
differentials in geography,

29:37.960 --> 29:40.090
-quality... -We get it, guys,
the odds are low.

29:40.130 --> 29:41.210
She doesn't even look Jewish.

29:41.250 --> 29:42.630
-Is she Jewish or...?
-We should leave.

29:42.670 --> 29:44.090
Papa, this is your celebration.

29:44.130 --> 29:45.590
Don't let him ruin it.

29:45.630 --> 29:46.890
I couldn't find
my Finchley cuff links.

29:46.930 --> 29:48.850
It was an omen.
I should have heeded it.

29:48.890 --> 29:50.140
Papa, your cuff links
were not an omen.

29:50.180 --> 29:51.680
Her ankles are the same size
as her calves.

29:51.720 --> 29:53.310
Okay, if we're gonna stay,
we should probably

29:53.350 --> 29:54.770
figure out something else
to be talking...

29:56.440 --> 29:58.020
We should go.

29:58.060 --> 29:59.520
Put the egg rolls in your purse.

29:59.560 --> 30:01.150
-My purse is silk.
-Fine.

30:01.190 --> 30:02.900
Anyone with pockets,
grab a roll.

30:02.940 --> 30:04.820
-I'll get us a cab.
-We should walk.

30:04.860 --> 30:06.910
-I'm in heels.
-Fine, we're getting a cab.

30:06.950 --> 30:08.620
-Noah, get us a cab.
-Okay.

30:12.580 --> 30:14.200
(car horn honks)

30:14.250 --> 30:16.080
ABE:
Taxi!

30:16.120 --> 30:18.880
-NOAH: Taxi?
-ABE: Hey. Taxi!

30:18.920 --> 30:20.290
-JOEL: Midge.
-Joel, please...

30:20.340 --> 30:21.920
-I'm sorry.
-It's okay.

30:21.960 --> 30:23.840
-I didn't know you'd be here.
-How could you?

30:23.880 --> 30:25.970
-I didn't know you came here.
-We don't. We never have.

30:26.010 --> 30:27.720
I've been steering clear of
Barney Greengrass and Zabar's.

30:27.760 --> 30:29.640
I go all the way over
to the East Side

30:29.680 --> 30:31.260
just to buy
a pack of cigarettes.

30:31.300 --> 30:32.600
We're celebrating.
It's a special occasion.

30:32.640 --> 30:34.430
My father got a job
at Bell Labs.

30:34.470 --> 30:37.140
Bell Labs? Wow, that's terrific.
He finally got it.

30:37.190 --> 30:38.480
It's a special occasion.
That-That's all.

30:38.520 --> 30:39.650
I'll never come here again.

30:39.690 --> 30:40.860
We'll never come here again.

30:40.900 --> 30:42.610
I'm sorry. I just...

30:42.650 --> 30:45.070
I didn't mean
to spoil the night.

30:45.110 --> 30:46.860
You didn't. It's...

30:57.250 --> 30:59.620
You should go back inside.

31:02.000 --> 31:04.880
Tell your...

31:04.920 --> 31:06.880
That's great...

31:06.920 --> 31:09.130
about Bell Labs.

31:23.110 --> 31:25.190
ASTRID:
And this is Rabbi Schneerson.

31:25.230 --> 31:27.190
A very good man,
but that card's in every pack,

31:27.240 --> 31:29.030
-so no one will trade you
for him. -(laughs)

31:29.070 --> 31:30.570
ROSE:
Capers and mustard.

31:30.610 --> 31:32.410
That's it for things
I recognize in here.

31:32.450 --> 31:34.200
We should have taken
the champagne.

31:34.240 --> 31:36.490
-It was already poured. -That's
why God invented funnels.

31:36.540 --> 31:38.160
No, wait, I see cottage cheese.

31:38.200 --> 31:40.330
-I like cottage cheese.
-(gasps) You got a Hirchensohn!

31:40.370 --> 31:42.460
Chief rabbi of Hoboken!

31:42.500 --> 31:44.460
(laughs) Have you ever seen
a Hirchensohn?

31:44.500 --> 31:46.590
To be honest, I've never seen
rabbi trading cards.

31:46.630 --> 31:48.130
Oh, one of the wonders
of Israel.

31:48.170 --> 31:49.720
That and Shabbat on a kibbutz.

31:49.760 --> 31:51.550
Okay, this might be soup
or gravy. I don't know.

31:51.590 --> 31:52.970
It's a container of brown--
should we try it?

31:53.010 --> 31:55.140
This is no longer
cottage cheese.

31:55.180 --> 31:57.100
ASTRID: I can't believe
someone actually came in here

31:57.140 --> 31:59.350
to steal the gefilte fish--
we could be eating that.

31:59.390 --> 32:01.810
-ROSE: Astonishing.
-You sure it's not here?

32:01.850 --> 32:03.810
-I looked.
-MIDGE: We looked.

32:03.860 --> 32:05.230
Can I go to bed now?

32:05.270 --> 32:06.780
-Oh...
-Of course, sweetie.

32:06.820 --> 32:09.150
Here, I'll take you.
Oh, and I can sneak in

32:09.190 --> 32:10.950
and steal a little kiss
for my baby Esther.

32:10.990 --> 32:12.910
Oh, no, uh, the baby
just went to sleep, Astrid.

32:12.950 --> 32:14.700
I promise you can kiss her
in the morning.

32:14.740 --> 32:16.530
Good night, Ethan.
Sweet dreams.

32:16.580 --> 32:19.000
(gasps)
Cookies. I found cookies.

32:19.040 --> 32:20.540
Oh, ignore
what your brother says--

32:20.580 --> 32:23.380
-you are officially
my favorite. Mmm. -Mmm.

32:23.420 --> 32:24.880
It's not going to last.

32:24.920 --> 32:27.300
-What's not?
-Joel and that woman.

32:27.340 --> 32:30.010
I saw him check
his watch. Twice.

32:30.050 --> 32:32.050
-Mama, don't...
-Trust me.

32:32.090 --> 32:34.930
That girl is on her way out.

32:43.600 --> 32:47.230
♪ You with the stars
in your eyes... ♪

32:47.270 --> 32:50.490
Cookie for a smoke?

32:50.530 --> 32:53.610
If the parents catch us,
this was your idea.

32:53.660 --> 32:55.820
-♪ You used to be ♪
-Yeah, yeah.

32:55.870 --> 32:58.330
-♪ Too wise ♪
-(horn honks in distance)

33:01.450 --> 33:03.670
♪ Hey there... ♪

33:03.710 --> 33:05.960
What a dinner, huh?

33:06.000 --> 33:08.000
What? Did something
unusual happen?

33:08.040 --> 33:09.750
I wasn't paying attention.

33:09.800 --> 33:11.840
I still can't believe
you and Joel split.

33:11.880 --> 33:13.430
Wasn't my plan, believe me.

33:13.470 --> 33:15.430
It's so disappointing.
I really liked the guy.

33:15.470 --> 33:17.050
God, and that girl he was with.

33:17.100 --> 33:19.680
When I saw that, I thought,
"I should hit him."

33:19.720 --> 33:21.270
And I would've.

33:21.310 --> 33:23.690
But then I remembered once
we were joking around,

33:23.730 --> 33:25.690
and I sort of
fake-punched his arm...

33:25.730 --> 33:27.150
Broke my pinkie.

33:27.190 --> 33:29.190
-What?
-He didn't look that big,

33:29.230 --> 33:31.190
but his arm
was like a brick wall.

33:31.230 --> 33:33.530
-Yeah, he had strong arms.
-It was humiliating.

33:33.570 --> 33:35.610
The next day at work
I had to make up a story

33:35.660 --> 33:38.070
-about being mugged in the park.
-You never told me any of this.

33:38.120 --> 33:39.870
Well... it wasn't my most...

33:39.910 --> 33:42.040
manly anecdote.

33:45.250 --> 33:48.420
I sure hate
that he hurt you, boy.

33:49.670 --> 33:51.630
Thanks.

33:51.670 --> 33:53.720
Make sure the next guy
you get involved with

33:53.760 --> 33:55.220
has very weak
upper body strength.

33:55.260 --> 33:57.010
-Of course.
-I'd like to defend your honor.

33:57.050 --> 33:58.930
-I'd appreciate that.
-But I have to be able

33:58.970 --> 34:00.890
to hold a pen the next day.

34:00.930 --> 34:03.560
Noah, listen,
you got to do me a favor, okay?

34:03.600 --> 34:04.770
Anything.

34:04.810 --> 34:06.350
Don't leave Astrid.

34:06.390 --> 34:07.980
Oh, my God.
I'm not gonna leave Astrid.

34:08.020 --> 34:09.440
-She thinks you are.
-I'm not.

34:09.480 --> 34:11.230
I've told her
a million times I'm not.

34:11.270 --> 34:13.030
-She's worried about h... -Kids.
I know, she's obsessed with it.

34:13.070 --> 34:15.489
I don't care if we have kids.
I want a dog.

34:15.530 --> 34:16.909
She's driving herself crazy.

34:16.949 --> 34:18.239
She's driving me crazy.

34:18.280 --> 34:19.659
I don't know
what to do with her.

34:19.699 --> 34:20.909
When she gets something
in her head--

34:20.949 --> 34:22.330
like the whole converting thing.

34:22.370 --> 34:24.909
She had to sign up for the
accelerated conversion package.

34:24.949 --> 34:26.370
Goy to Jew
in three weeks or less.

34:26.409 --> 34:28.540
Classes, rituals,
and weird baths in basements,

34:28.580 --> 34:30.840
and, oh, my God,
so much challah.

34:30.880 --> 34:32.340
-I remember.
-All to impress Mama.

34:32.380 --> 34:33.550
Who doesn't eat bread.

34:33.590 --> 34:35.130
And if I have to go to Israel

34:35.170 --> 34:36.590
-one more time...
-Just, please,

34:36.630 --> 34:39.260
till death do you part.

34:40.510 --> 34:42.469
I promise.

34:42.510 --> 34:45.480
She's a lucky gal.

34:45.520 --> 34:47.480
I should get back in.

34:47.520 --> 34:49.520
I'm playing hooky.

34:53.780 --> 34:55.820
-Hey, your old turntable.
-(short chuckle)

34:55.860 --> 34:58.240
And some really dirty
comedy albums.

34:58.280 --> 34:59.740
Don't tell Mama.

34:59.780 --> 35:01.240
Vestiges of Joel?

35:01.280 --> 35:03.580
Nope, they're mine.

35:03.620 --> 35:05.370
You know...

35:05.410 --> 35:07.620
I never did get
his thing for comedy.

35:07.660 --> 35:10.290
One time we came to see him,
he didn't seem that funny.

35:10.330 --> 35:12.250
-Hmm.
-You're the funny one.

35:12.290 --> 35:14.300
You've always been
the funny one.

35:14.340 --> 35:16.630
-Thanks.
-(baby starts crying)

35:16.670 --> 35:18.090
Astrid kissed the baby.

35:18.130 --> 35:20.130
It was inevitable.

35:24.640 --> 35:28.180
The food was good.

35:28.230 --> 35:31.230
I wonder if there really was
a General Tso.

35:40.320 --> 35:41.990
You get out.

35:42.030 --> 35:45.160
I, uh, have to go back
to the office for a while.

35:45.200 --> 35:46.660
Oh.

35:46.700 --> 35:48.710
Okay.

35:53.170 --> 35:54.670
Don't wait up.

36:08.350 --> 36:09.980
Who the hell are you?

36:10.020 --> 36:11.940
Susie Myerson.
Nice to meet you.

36:11.980 --> 36:14.110
The, uh, African masks
seem out of place.

36:14.150 --> 36:16.070
-How did you get in here?
-Are you kidding me?

36:16.110 --> 36:18.650
The entire William Morris Agency
goes to lunch from 1:00 to 2:00.

36:18.690 --> 36:20.700
Agents, secretaries,
security, the janitor.

36:20.740 --> 36:22.360
I could've done naked cartwheels
down the corridor

36:22.410 --> 36:23.820
and no one
would have stopped me.

36:23.870 --> 36:25.740
What is it with you people
and lunch?

36:25.780 --> 36:28.490
-Don't any of you eat breakfast?
-Get out from behind my desk.

36:28.540 --> 36:31.210
I-I'm sorry, you don't like
people behind your desk?

36:31.250 --> 36:33.960
Tell you what.
I won't get behind your desk

36:34.000 --> 36:35.750
if you won't get behind mine.

36:35.790 --> 36:37.590
Okay, I'm calling security.

36:37.630 --> 36:39.710
Oh, forget it, Lew.
I cut the lines.

36:39.760 --> 36:41.510
You what?

36:41.550 --> 36:43.800
Ah, I didn't cut the lines.
Just wanted to sound like

36:43.840 --> 36:46.720
I was in a Bogart picture for
a second. It was kind of cool.

36:46.760 --> 36:48.720
Who the fuck are you?

36:48.770 --> 36:50.680
You handle a guy,
Randall something.

36:50.730 --> 36:53.350
I don't know the last name.
He's a client of yours, right?

36:53.390 --> 36:55.270
Introduced you to a woman
named Midge Maisel?

36:55.310 --> 36:56.770
Yeah, so?

36:56.810 --> 36:58.860
So? Midge Maisel's
a client of mine.

36:58.900 --> 37:00.860
-You're her rep?
-Yup.

37:00.900 --> 37:02.780
And she doesn't need
a William Morris agent

37:02.820 --> 37:05.280
in her life right now. She's got
everything she needs with me.

37:05.320 --> 37:07.780
And who are you,
to be telling me this?

37:07.830 --> 37:10.700
Lew, we both know what a place
like this does with someone

37:10.750 --> 37:13.290
like Midge--
a girl comic, good-looking,

37:13.330 --> 37:15.420
just starting out, can't sing.

37:15.460 --> 37:18.630
You meet 'em at the deli,
like you did, all casual-like.

37:18.670 --> 37:21.260
And then you schedule a fancy
lunch-- there's always lunch--

37:21.300 --> 37:23.300
talk to 'em about
their hopes and their dreams,

37:23.340 --> 37:25.130
you promise them everything,
you deliver nothing,

37:25.180 --> 37:27.010
and then you dump 'em
if lightning doesn't strike

37:27.050 --> 37:28.510
within the first five minutes.

37:28.550 --> 37:30.010
She does not need you.

37:30.060 --> 37:31.930
She does not need Randall.
She needs me.

37:31.980 --> 37:33.310
-Oh, yeah?
-Yeah.

37:33.350 --> 37:34.770
What kind of contract
you got with her?

37:34.810 --> 37:36.650
Same kind of contract
you got with your nuts--

37:36.690 --> 37:38.560
there's two of us
and we're attached.

37:38.610 --> 37:40.400
And if you ever
go near Midge again,

37:40.440 --> 37:42.780
I will make it
my life's mission to take you

37:42.820 --> 37:44.820
and this entire building down.

37:46.530 --> 37:49.580
Oh, and... here's my card.

37:49.620 --> 37:51.620
In case you need it someday.

37:57.040 --> 37:59.040
♪ ♪

38:04.300 --> 38:06.010
(knocking)

38:08.470 --> 38:09.930
(turns off radio)

38:12.350 --> 38:13.930
Babka.

38:13.980 --> 38:16.310
-Bourbon.
-Oh, I like that combination.

38:16.350 --> 38:18.600
Come in.

38:18.650 --> 38:21.480
It's excellent toasted
with a little butter,

38:21.520 --> 38:23.480
-if you're so inclined.
-(sniffs) Mm.

38:23.530 --> 38:24.820
Sit down.

38:24.860 --> 38:26.820
I like what you've done
with the place.

38:26.860 --> 38:29.620
-Do you?
-Yes. It looks...

38:29.660 --> 38:31.780
What shall we toast to?

38:31.830 --> 38:33.620
Not yet.
I want to talk first.

38:33.660 --> 38:35.250
Oh. Okay. Sounds serious.

38:35.290 --> 38:37.000
-You got a phone.
-I did.

38:37.040 --> 38:38.960
You said you
didn't get the phone.

38:39.000 --> 38:41.000
-Yeah, well,
I'm a cockeyed optimist. -Hmm.

38:41.040 --> 38:42.800
So, how you doing?

38:42.840 --> 38:44.210
I'm fine.

38:44.260 --> 38:46.590
Good. Good.
So you're not insane?

38:46.630 --> 38:48.720
-I don't think so.
-'Cause you seem insane.

38:48.760 --> 38:50.260
What are you talking about?

38:50.300 --> 38:52.100
This party circuit thing
you've got going on,

38:52.140 --> 38:54.060
I don't know
what you really think it is,

38:54.100 --> 38:55.480
but it's not stand-up.

38:55.520 --> 38:57.390
It's not a gig, it's a party.

38:57.440 --> 39:00.400
Yeah? You are not getting paid,
you are not getting booked,

39:00.440 --> 39:02.230
and those people
are not a real audience--

39:02.270 --> 39:04.730
they are politely nodding at you
while they drink free booze,

39:04.780 --> 39:06.610
and then they talk
about the crazy lady

39:06.650 --> 39:08.490
who wouldn't shut up
the whole night.

39:08.530 --> 39:10.070
I know they're not real gigs.

39:10.110 --> 39:11.820
Do you? 'Cause it
doesn't seem like it.

39:11.870 --> 39:13.990
-And second of all...
-There was no first of all.

39:14.040 --> 39:16.750
...you do not need a goddamn man
at your side to do this.

39:16.790 --> 39:18.460
What the hell are you thinking?

39:18.500 --> 39:20.790
You really want to be some
second-rate Nichols and May?

39:20.830 --> 39:22.710
'Cause there's already
a first-rate Nichols and May.

39:22.750 --> 39:24.420
It's fuckin' Nichols and May.

39:24.460 --> 39:27.510
Now, you could be an original,
but you are fucking it all up

39:27.550 --> 39:30.550
with this cockamamie alternate
universe party bullshit.

39:30.590 --> 39:32.430
You want to do this?!

39:32.470 --> 39:33.850
-Yes.
-Do you?

39:33.890 --> 39:35.890
-Yes!
-Well, I can't tell anymore.

39:35.930 --> 39:37.810
You want me to get rid of
the phone, 'cause I can get rid

39:37.850 --> 39:39.310
-of the phone.
-Do not get rid of the phone.

39:39.350 --> 39:40.560
I don't need
to have a goddamn phone.

39:40.600 --> 39:41.940
I don't have anybody
I have to call.

39:41.980 --> 39:43.690
I got that phone for you,

39:43.730 --> 39:46.030
for this partnership
that I thought we were starting.

39:46.070 --> 39:48.240
-We are.
-Does your new agent know that?

39:48.280 --> 39:49.530
He's... not my...

39:49.570 --> 39:51.910
You do not meet
with any agents

39:51.950 --> 39:54.330
without me knowing
about it, ever.

39:54.370 --> 39:56.450
I did not know he was
gonna be there. I swear.

39:56.490 --> 39:58.870
Bullshit! You're not an idiot!

39:58.910 --> 40:01.420
Just drop this doe-eyed
Bambi thing right now.

40:01.460 --> 40:04.380
Okay, I'm so sick of you
acting all innocent: "Oh,

40:04.420 --> 40:06.920
"I don't know how the world
works 'cause I'm a housewife,

40:06.960 --> 40:08.710
and I wear four layers
of petticoats."

40:08.760 --> 40:10.420
It is tired and it is weak,

40:10.470 --> 40:12.970
and you are not tired
and you are not fucking weak.

40:13.010 --> 40:14.890
And if you want to be a comic,

40:14.930 --> 40:17.970
you are gonna have
to grow the fuck up right now!

40:18.020 --> 40:20.100
(whimpers)

40:20.140 --> 40:22.350
(sniffles)

40:22.400 --> 40:25.400
(sobbing)

40:25.440 --> 40:28.610
(sniffles)
I'm sorry. I...

40:28.650 --> 40:30.360
I don't know what to do lately.

40:30.400 --> 40:32.860
I'm... I'm trying to be strong
and independent,

40:32.910 --> 40:35.660
but I saw Joel the other night,
and he was with her,

40:35.700 --> 40:38.870
and every time I think
I can breathe again, I can't.

40:38.910 --> 40:40.540
And I'm-I'm trying
to get it right.

40:40.580 --> 40:42.080
I'm trying to figure it out.

40:42.120 --> 40:43.750
I know the parties aren't gigs.

40:43.790 --> 40:45.670
I know I'm not
really doing stand-up.

40:45.710 --> 40:47.750
I don't want to be
a second-rate Nichols and May.

40:47.800 --> 40:49.510
I'd never even heard
of Nichols and May.

40:49.550 --> 40:50.970
And I've got news for you.

40:51.010 --> 40:52.930
If you're gonna be
a personal manager,

40:52.970 --> 40:55.640
then sometimes you're gonna have
to deal with the personal.

40:55.680 --> 40:57.220
And this...

40:57.260 --> 40:58.810
is personal.

40:58.850 --> 41:00.350
All of this.

41:00.390 --> 41:03.100
And it's not
just deals and lectures.

41:03.140 --> 41:05.270
Sometimes you're gonna have
to buy some Kleenex

41:05.310 --> 41:07.480
and let me cry
and pat me on the back

41:07.520 --> 41:09.650
-and say, "There, there."
-Okay, that's not really my...

41:09.690 --> 41:10.940
You're gonna have
to listen to me talk

41:10.990 --> 41:12.570
about my husband,
and my kids.

41:12.610 --> 41:14.200
Both of 'em?

41:14.240 --> 41:15.910
Yes. Both of them.

41:15.950 --> 41:19.120
And you are gonna have
to stop backing away from me

41:19.160 --> 41:21.950
when I feel like my life
is falling apart.

41:22.000 --> 41:25.460
You are gonna have to tell me
I'm good when I'm not.

41:25.500 --> 41:27.040
-You want me to lie?
-Yes!

41:27.080 --> 41:29.050
That is what managers do!

41:29.090 --> 41:31.760
Do you understand?

41:31.800 --> 41:33.470
(Midge exhales)

41:34.470 --> 41:36.300
(Midge crying quietly)

41:38.260 --> 41:39.640
(sobs)

41:42.810 --> 41:44.770
There, there.

41:46.850 --> 41:48.560
Better?

41:50.940 --> 41:53.570
(sniffles)
Yes.

41:53.610 --> 41:55.700
Better.

41:55.740 --> 41:57.240
Good.

41:57.280 --> 41:58.990
Tomorrow...

41:59.030 --> 42:02.120
we're gonna sign
some fuckin' paperwork.

42:04.160 --> 42:06.710
The last few signatures.
I promise.

42:06.750 --> 42:08.500
Responsibility is often

42:08.540 --> 42:11.500
-accompanied by
excessive paperwork. -And how.

42:11.550 --> 42:13.210
Especially when
the government's involved.

42:13.260 --> 42:15.220
If you'd asked me a week ago,
I would not have put money

42:15.260 --> 42:16.470
on us sitting here today.

42:16.510 --> 42:18.390
Well, I had to shuffle
quite a few things around,

42:18.430 --> 42:22.390
make some tough compromises,
and you seemed so desperate.

42:22.430 --> 42:24.520
We are thrilled, believe me.

42:24.560 --> 42:25.770
All your background checks
are completed.

42:25.810 --> 42:27.020
You sailed through

42:27.060 --> 42:28.230
-faster than most.
-Very good.

42:28.270 --> 42:30.480
Now, there's just
the final government clearance.

42:30.520 --> 42:33.690
It's somewhat more intensive,
but it should go smoothly, too.

42:33.730 --> 42:35.400
The only possible bump I see

42:35.440 --> 42:36.860
would be
your daughter's arrests.

42:38.110 --> 42:40.990
Her arrests?

42:41.030 --> 42:42.580
We know, a couple of
misdemeanors, she pled guilty.

42:42.620 --> 42:44.290
It shouldn't be
too big a problem.

42:44.330 --> 42:46.750
Right. Yes.

42:46.790 --> 42:48.290
Young people go through
these phases, right?

42:48.330 --> 42:51.420
Yes, young people go
through phases.

42:51.460 --> 42:52.920
Things I did in college,
it's amazing my parents

42:52.960 --> 42:54.010
still talk to me.

42:54.050 --> 42:56.840
(chuckles)

42:56.880 --> 42:58.720
We'll ease you in
the first couple of days.

42:58.760 --> 43:01.220
One of us will take you
on a tour of the facility,

43:01.260 --> 43:02.260
get you oriented.

43:02.310 --> 43:03.890
Might be me,
might be my colleague, Sven.

43:03.930 --> 43:05.470
Sven is a great fellow.

43:05.520 --> 43:07.980
MIDGE: I was cornered by
Mrs. Klaviter today. -ROSE: Mm.

43:08.020 --> 43:09.730
Ever since she kicked Junie Paul
in the shins,

43:09.770 --> 43:11.690
-I run when I see her. -She
starts telling me this story

43:11.730 --> 43:13.270
-about her mother's health.
-Mm.

43:13.320 --> 43:15.650
And right as she says
she's only got a month to live,

43:15.690 --> 43:17.530
the baby starts laughing.

43:17.570 --> 43:20.820
I tell you, it was
the world's longest pause.

43:20.870 --> 43:23.740
But then,
Mrs. Klaviter laughed, too.

43:23.780 --> 43:26.160
Turns out, she hates her mother
and thinks Esther's a delight.

43:26.200 --> 43:27.410
(Rose laughs)

43:27.460 --> 43:28.870
(chuckles)

43:28.910 --> 43:30.170
What?

43:35.050 --> 43:36.260
ROSE: What ever happened
to Junie Paul?

43:36.300 --> 43:38.510
I wonder if she ever married.

43:38.550 --> 43:40.050
I would think.

43:40.090 --> 43:41.680
ROSE: She just needed to
keep her hair long enough

43:41.720 --> 43:44.010
-to cover those ears.
-They were enormous,

43:44.060 --> 43:45.560
but she could hear
someone whispering

43:45.600 --> 43:46.850
from across a football field.
I'm kidding.

43:46.890 --> 43:47.890
MIDGE (on tape):
I was fun.

43:47.930 --> 43:49.140
I planned theme nights,

43:49.190 --> 43:51.230
I dressed in costumes,

43:51.270 --> 43:54.440
I gave him kids,
a boy and a girl! And yes,

43:54.480 --> 43:56.190
our little girl is looking more
and more like Winston Churchill

43:56.230 --> 43:57.990
-every day, with the big...
-(men laughing)

43:58.030 --> 44:01.610
Yalta-head? But that's not
a reason to leave, right?

44:01.660 --> 44:03.530
Really? Really? After what
I just said about the bathroom?

44:03.570 --> 44:05.200
OZ: It's like she's having
a breakdown.

44:05.240 --> 44:07.080
-VIRGIL: But it's hysterical.
-OZ: It's amazing.

44:07.120 --> 44:09.210
MIDGE (on tape):
Walk of shame!

44:09.250 --> 44:10.790
VIRGIL:
It's total improv.

44:10.830 --> 44:12.420
OZ:
Nah, this had to be written.

44:12.460 --> 44:15.590
MIDGE (on tape):
And I showed him I loved him.

44:15.630 --> 44:17.760
All that shit they say
about Jewish girls...

44:17.800 --> 44:19.800
OZ: Well, whatever it is,
it's genius.

44:19.840 --> 44:22.220
-VIRGIL: Pure genius. -OZ: And
you don't know who she is?

44:22.260 --> 44:24.100
VIRGIL: All we know is she's
married to some guy named Joel,

44:24.140 --> 44:25.720
and she lives uptown.

44:25.760 --> 44:27.560
OZ: Let's dub a hundred
and see where it goes.

44:27.600 --> 44:29.640
(audience laughing on tape)

44:29.680 --> 44:31.350
MIDGE (on tape): I can't believe
this is happening.

44:31.390 --> 44:34.610
I can't believe I'm losing him
to Penny Pann.

44:34.650 --> 44:36.690
That's her name.
Terrible right?

44:36.730 --> 44:38.480
-(Oz and Virgil laughing)
-MIDGE: Penny Pann!

44:38.530 --> 44:40.240
Penny Pann.

44:40.280 --> 44:42.410
-Penny Pann!
-(audience laughs and cheers)

44:42.450 --> 44:44.820
("Our Lips Are Sealed"
by the Go-Go's plays)

44:58.090 --> 45:00.300
♪ Can you hear them? ♪

45:00.340 --> 45:02.340
♪ They talk about us ♪

45:02.380 --> 45:03.760
♪ Telling lies ♪

45:03.800 --> 45:05.260
♪ Well, that's no surprise ♪

45:05.300 --> 45:07.050
♪ Can you see them? ♪

45:07.100 --> 45:10.350
